The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Travel rules for babus eased
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Travel rules for babus eased
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                                            
	New Delhi, March 24: Come April 1, eligible government officials will fly first class as the austerity drive on travel ends. However, if they are on a holiday, the regulation will continue.        
	The restrictions were imposed in September last year in the wake of the global financial crisis.        
	The (expenditure management) matter has been reviewed and it has been decided that with effect from April 1, 2010, travel on government account by air, both domestic and international, may take place by the entitled class, an official memorandum by the department of expenditure said.        
	However, the government has not relaxed the austerity directive in case of leave travel concession (LTC).         
	Austerity measures will remain in place for travel by air (where admissible) on LTC, which would continue to be restricted to economy class, irrespective of the entitlement, it said.        
	Last Septembers government directive had forced ministers and senior officials to cut down on foreign travel.         
	The finance ministry issued directives that ministers and bureaucrats must fly Air India, the official carrier. They were forbidden from holding press conferences, seminars and other events at five-star hotels.        
	Income tax ID        
	The government plans to introduce a unique document identification number to be quoted on every income tax related communication. The number will be mandatory while filing the annual income tax return from financial year 2010-11.        
	The number will be generated by the IT department and will be useful for error-free filing of tax returns, claiming refunds and other communication with the department by the assesses, a senior finance ministry official said.                                                                                                                                                   
